{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17489193","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17489193"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T04:08:28+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T04:08:28+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"614"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"614","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/614"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.38,0.04,0.06,0.51,0.02]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"614"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"115430"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"614","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/614"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"614"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"97434"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"1"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"98"},{"type":"tags","id":"106"},{"type":"tags","id":"480"},{"type":"tags","id":"1453"},{"type":"tags","id":"2665"},{"type":"tags","id":"5064"},{"type":"tags","id":"12922"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"1592"},{"type":"contributions","id":"1703"},{"type":"contributions","id":"7495"},{"type":"contributions","id":"14193"},{"type":"contributions","id":"36593"},{"type":"contributions","id":"36643"},{"type":"contributions","id":"39978"},{"type":"contributions","id":"39979"},{"type":"contributions","id":"41902"},{"type":"contributions","id":"45353"},{"type":"contributions","id":"45358"},{"type":"contributions","id":"48561"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"115430","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/115430"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 50-year-old man is seen in the pre-operative assessment clinic in advance of an elective total knee replacement. The surgeon has told him that this procedure will require a stay in hospital. The patient\u2019s medical history includes atrial fibrillation secondary to mitral stenosis, type 2 diabetes, hypertension, and hypercholesterolaemia. His medications include warfarin, metformin/sitagliptin, dapagliflozin, amlodipine, and atorvastatin.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn physical examination, the patient is generally well with vitals and blood glucose levels within normal limits. His BMI is estimated to be 24, and his most recent is eGFR is \u0026gt;90.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe patient is assessed as fit to proceed with the planned operation.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate advice regarding management of the patient\u0027s medications?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Dapagliflozin should be held from 2 days prior to and the day of the procedure","Amlodipine should be held on the morning of the procedure","Metformin/sitagliptin should be continued perioperatively","Warfarin should be held 5 days prior without bridging anticoagulation","Atorvastatin should be held from the day prior and restarted once normal diet resumes"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe correct answer is that \u0027\u003Cstrong\u003Edapagliflozin should be held from 2 days before the procedure and the day of the procedure\u003C/strong\u003E\u0027 (i.e. for 72 hours). Dapagliflozin is a sodium-glucose co-transporter-2 (SGLT2) inhibitor, a class associated with the rare but serious complication of euglycaemic ketoacidosis in the setting of intercurrent illness, surgical stress, volume depletion, and dietary modification including perioperative fasting and reduced carbohydrate intake.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe pathophysiology is complex, but centres on SGLT2-mediated increase in hepatic ketogenesis and renal ketone reabsorption. Current evidence suggests withholding SGLT2 inhibitors immediately for emergency procedures, from at least 2-3 days prior to elective surgery (based on a terminal half-life of approximately 12 hours), and for up to 2 weeks prior to bariatric procedures where a strict low-carbohydrate diet is introduced preoperatively. These agents can then be restarted postoperatively once the patient is clinically well, euvolaemic, and tolerating oral intake.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAmlodipine should be held on the morning of the procedure\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect. It can be safely continued perioperatively in the absence of haemodynamic instability, and should generally be\u003Cstrong\u003E \u003C/strong\u003Econtinued to prevent hypertension.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMetformin/sitagliptin should be continued preoperatively is incorrect.\u003C/strong\u003E Metformin/sitagliptin should be held on the morning of the procedure while the patient is fasting, given the risk of preoperative hypoglycaemia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPerioperative anticoagulation management requires careful consideration of the bleeding and thrombotic risks. This patient is on regular warfarin due to AF secondary to mitral stenosis, which carries a high thromboembolic risk. Hence, \u003Cstrong\u003Ebridging anticoagulation \u003C/strong\u003Eis required in addition to \u003Cstrong\u003Ewithholding warfarin 5 days prior \u003C/strong\u003Eto surgery. A general approach would be to withhold warfarin, test INR daily and start a low molecular-weight heparin or unfractionated heparin when INR is sub-therapeutic.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAtorvastatin\u003C/strong\u003E can be safely continued perioperatively.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["SGLT2 inhibitors should be held at least 2 days prior to a procedure due to the risk of euglycaemic ketoacidosis."],"references":["Thiruvenkatarajan V, Meyer E, Nanjappa N, Van Wijk R, Jesudason D. Perioperative diabetic ketoacidosis associated with sodium-glucose co-transporter-2 inhibitors: a systematic review. British Journal of Anaesthesia. 2019;123(1):27-36.","Pannucci CJ, Swistun L, Macdonald JK, Henke PK, Brooke BS. Individualized Venous Thromboembolism Risk Stratification Using the 2005 Caprini Score to Identify the Benefits and Harms of Chemoprophylaxis in Surgical Patients: A Meta-analysis. Ann Surg. 2017;","Zala A, Maple-Brown LJ, Shaw JE, et al. Current evidence and practical guidance for\u00a0the use of sodiumglucose co-transporter-2 inhibitors in type 2 diabetes. Aust J Gen Pract. 2021; 50: 225-30.","Clinical Excellence Commission, 2025, Guidelines on Periprocedural Management of Anticoagulant and Antiplatelet Agents. Sydney: Clinical Excellence Commission"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"97434"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"614"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"97434","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/97434"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-23T17:31:02+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-23T17:31:46+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"614"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"115430"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"1","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/1"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude34","name":"Anaesthesia","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"upd